0439587f-52ea-4ebd-b9fc-e52a0380a536.11e3e664-2589-45b3-942d-52e45a746fe9.description=Purpose\:
 Moves all cluster resource groups owned by the target node off. This step can be used prior to restarting a cluster node, to ensure that no clustered services are impacted.	 
 
Return Code\:
 0 \= Current node does not own any cluster resource groups.
 Other \= Error in gathering cluster resource group information, or in moving process.

Inputs\:
 command - executes WindowsMoveClusterGroups.py
 Cluster Groups to Take Ownership - A comma-delimited list of the cluster resource groups to be owned by the current node. A blank value will relinquish all resource groups currently owned by the node. Optional, String.
 host - Target to run this command against
 password - Login information for host
 username - Login information for host
 protocol - ssh/wmi
 timeout - Time (ms) before auto-exit\: use ${ExtendedTimeout} to lengthen.

Results\:
 Cluster Groups Moved - A comma-delimited list of the cluster resource groups that were moved from/to the current node.
 Exit Code - Exit code of the step needed for branching.

 0439587f-52ea-4ebd-b9fc-e52a0380a536.description=<pre>
 Description

This workflow installs a SQL Server patch on a clustered 2008/2008R2/2012 instance.
The default deployment will only show required parameters.
To execute the workflow, only one of the nodes in the cluster needs to be a target for the deployment. The workflow will discover all cluster members and patch each one.
The workflow will first patch all inactive nodes, then it will failover the instance in order to make the active node a passive node, and patch that remaining node.

 Required Inputs

 Server Target - The desired target to run this flow against.
 Server Target Username - The user to login to the Server Target as.
 Server Target Password - The password to login as the Server Target Username.
 Download Source Host - The target host where the files needed for this flow can be downloaded from.
 Download Source Path - The path to where the files can be found on the Download Source Host.
 Download From Software Directory - *Required. The path to the patch file in the Software Repository. If file already exists on local system, ensure that the filename is entered into this field, and the file's directory is entered into the "Download Target Destination" parameter.
 Download Target Destination - *Required. The directory where the patch file should be stored. If it doesn't exist in this directory, it will be downloaded from the software repository, using the path provided in the "Download From Software Directory" parameter.
 Instance - Name of the MS SQL Instance to have patch applied.
 Server.Name - No description

 Optional Inputs

 Clean Code Base - Remove code base from target after execution (True || False).
 Clean JRE - Remove JRE from target after execution (True || False).
 Download From SA - Download binaries from SA (True || False). Must set override for 'SAUser' System Account.
 SA Folder Path - Location of binaries on SA. Must set override for 'SAUser' System Account.
 Debug Level - Set level of output [(least) 1-5 (most)]
 Never Restart - No description
 Installer Password - Password of Windows account that will be performing the install. Must be a strong Windows password.
 Network Share File - Optional. Path to the patch file on a Windows network share. Path should begin with "\\"."
 Backup Type - Optional - backup type; valid values are FULL, LOG, DIFFERENTIAL, COPY-ONLY, COPY-ONLY LOG. If none is provided, FULL backup will be taken.
 Patch All Instances on Server - No description
 Installer Account - Windows account that will be performing the install. Acceptable value is in format [DOMAIN]\[USERNAME]
 Cluster Administrator Password - *Required for patches on clustered instances. Password for the domain user that will run the setup operation; requires elevated administrator privileges on the cluster. Must be a strong Windows password.
 Backup Path - Optional. Specifies the location for the backups of SQL Server databases. If left blank, the Instance default setting will be used.
 Cluster Administrator Account - *Required for patches on clustered instances. Domain user that will run the setup operation; requires elevated administrator privileges on the cluster. Acceptable value is in format [DOMAIN]\[USERNAME]

 Dependencies

A SQL Server 2008/2008R2/2012 clustered instance should already be provisioned.
Patch installation media should on the Software Repository, be mounted locally, or available to the agent's user via Windows network share, prior to running this workflow.

 Results Verification

- In the last step, the workflow verifies that the SQL Server instance's build level matches that of the patch file
- Run "SELECT @@VERSION" against the SQL Server Instance to ensure that the build level matches that of file's FileVersion property (found by right-clicking file on Windows, and selecting Properties).



 Additional Documentation

Additional information, including the _HP Database and Middleware Automation Support Matrix_ and solution pack user guides, are available via HP Live Network\:

"http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation"\:http\://hpln.hp.com/group/database-and-middleware-automation

To access the documentation, click the RESOURCES link and enter your HP Passport credentials.
</pre> 0439587f-52ea-4ebd-b9fc-e52a0380a536.e3166c05-beac-49f7-a7bd-3168b0606592.description=
